WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.055
Open Settings, and expand the Operations group.

p02
00:00:04.346 --> 00:00:08.576
These lists are the raw material for dropdowns all over the platform.

p03
00:00:09.239 --> 00:00:12.051
When a cashier reaches for a reason and it isn't there,

p04
00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:15.760
the fix lives on one of these pages, not in the register.

p05
00:00:16.231 --> 00:00:17.912
Open Cancellation Reasons.

p06
00:00:18.672 --> 00:00:19.733
Two columns here.

p07
00:00:20.064 --> 00:00:21.262
One names the reason, the other decides whether a cashier ever sees it.

p08
00:00:21.524 --> 00:00:24.594
That second column, Show on P-O-S, is the one to check first

p09
00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:32.466
when a reason exists but never shows up at the register.

p10
00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:35.031
Look at the list body.

p11
00:00:35.031 --> 00:00:36.267
Thirty-three reasons, loaded live.

p12
00:00:36.267 --> 00:00:40.874
The tiles above count thirty shown at the register and three kept hidden,

p13
00:00:40.874 --> 00:00:44.681
and the footer pages you through the full set.

p14
00:00:44.681 --> 00:00:47.769
Those three hidden rows read No in the second column:

p15
00:00:47.769 --> 00:00:50.240
still on the books, invisible to the cashier.

p16
00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:52.359
Now Refund Reasons.

p17
00:00:52.802 --> 00:00:54.527
One column, one job: it fills the reason picker on the refund screen.

p18
00:00:54.959 --> 00:00:57.331
This tenant's list is genuinely empty, zero reasons,

p19
00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:05.381
with a note that the P-O-S database may not be configured yet.

p20
00:01:05.704 --> 00:01:08.772
That is a real empty state, not a load error.

p21
00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:11.244
Rewash Reasons, same idea.

p22
00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:15.678
This is the list an attendant picks from when a car goes back through the wash.

p23
00:01:16.046 --> 00:01:20.596
Twelve reasons live here, everything from bugs on the car to wheels not clean.

p24
00:01:20.965 --> 00:01:24.480
Identical shape to refunds, just with its rows filled in.

p25
00:01:24.945 --> 00:01:26.151
Two more, back to back.

p26
00:01:26.442 --> 00:01:28.743
Event Types, then Transaction Types.

p27
00:01:29.341 --> 00:01:33.343
One classifies things that happen, the other classifies money that moves,

p28
00:01:33.695 --> 00:01:35.243
and reporting leans on both.

p29
00:01:35.877 --> 00:01:39.166
The layout never changes: a description column and a count.

p30
00:01:39.742 --> 00:01:40.770
Issue Status Types.

p31
00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:45.279
This one loaded, so you can see the real values.

p32
00:01:45.279 --> 00:01:47.678
Open, in progress, pending parts, resolved, closed.

p33
00:01:47.678 --> 00:01:51.351
Those five are the stages an issue walks through,

p34
00:01:51.351 --> 00:01:55.120
and they're the same labels you'll meet on ticket records elsewhere.

p35
00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:57.565
Switch groups, over to Automation.

p36
00:01:57.938 --> 00:01:59.736
This is where the background jobs live:

p37
00:02:00.085 --> 00:02:03.139
the scheduler, its parameters, and the mass text log.

p38
00:02:03.508 --> 00:02:07.980
User Levels sits here too, but that's a security page, and it's covered on its own.

p39
00:02:08.459 --> 00:02:09.374
Open Task Scheduler.

p40
00:02:09.374 --> 00:02:11.236
Read the tiles first.

p41
00:02:11.236 --> 00:02:17.836
They sum up the whole job list at a glance, and the one that earns your attention is Failed.

p42
00:02:17.836 --> 00:02:19.971
When someone says a job didn't run,

p43
00:02:19.971 --> 00:02:24.240
a non-zero Failed count is your fastest signal, before you open a single row.

p44
00:02:24.693 --> 00:02:26.016
Now the list itself.

p45
00:02:26.638 --> 00:02:28.809
Five columns tell you a job's name, its schedule, when it last ran,

p46
00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:31.107
when it runs next, and its status.

p47
00:02:31.313 --> 00:02:33.536
The daily report email is right here.

p48
00:02:34.201 --> 00:02:42.000
If it never arrived, read last run and status on that row before you blame the mailbox.

p49
00:02:42.463 --> 00:02:45.031
Notice the new-record and filter controls.

p50
00:02:45.493 --> 00:02:46.564
You read this page.

p51
00:02:46.915 --> 00:02:50.277
You never edit a schedule, and you never run a task.

p52
00:02:51.470 --> 00:02:52.716
One quirk worth knowing: today the header claims eighteen tasks,

p53
00:02:53.109 --> 00:02:57.525
but only three rows actually rendered.

p54
00:02:57.853 --> 00:02:59.138
The rest we've parked.

p55
00:02:59.665 --> 00:03:00.772
Task Parameters.

p56
00:03:01.315 --> 00:03:04.478
These are the reusable inputs the jobs read when they run.

p57
00:03:04.756 --> 00:03:09.329
The updated-by and updated columns tell you who last changed one, and when,

p58
00:03:09.575 --> 00:03:12.842
which is exactly what you want the day a job starts behaving differently.

p59
00:03:13.803 --> 00:03:15.549
Rows are loading from the service.

p60
00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:17.913
Last page. Mass S-M-S Log.

p61
00:03:18.374 --> 00:03:20.124
This is the delivery record for mass texts.

p62
00:03:20.687 --> 00:03:23.022
When a customer swears they never got the message,

p63
00:03:23.503 --> 00:03:29.214
the status column is where you confirm whether it actually went out.

p64
00:03:29.761 --> 00:03:32.345
Same load error today, so the rows are pending.

p65
00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:35.295
So, two groups, two kinds of ticket.

p66
00:03:35.295 --> 00:03:39.524
Operations feeds the dropdowns, so a missing reason ends there,

p67
00:03:39.524 --> 00:03:43.091
and Show on P-O-S decides what a cashier sees.

p68
00:03:43.091 --> 00:03:47.304
Automation runs the jobs, so a report that never came

p69
00:03:47.304 --> 00:03:50.659
starts at the scheduler's last run and status.

p70
00:03:50.659 --> 00:03:54.580
Learn which page owns which question, and the triage answers itself.

